8. Trust Decision Framework
The Problem: Wrong Answer Merging
When operators disagree on numerical queries, naively merging their answers can produce incorrect results. For example, one operator might retrieve the exact XBRL-tagged revenue figure while the other retrieves a narrative approximation. Averaging these would produce an incorrect answer.
Evidence Authority Hierarchy
Node Type	Authority Score	Rationale
FINANCIAL_LINE	1.00	XBRL-tagged, audited data
TABLE_ROW	0.90	XBRL-tagged, audited data
TABLE	0.85	Structured tabular data
TEXT_SECTION	0.60	Narrative context
NOTE	0.50	Narrative context
ENTITY	0.40	Requires additional context
Trust Decision Logic (from mode_selection.py)
Threshold	Value	Purpose
FINANCIAL_DOMINANCE_THRESHOLD	0.55	Min ratio to trust one operator for numerical queries
RELIABILITY_GAP_THRESHOLD	0.25	Min gap to trust more reliable operator
Answer Agreement	0.10	Delta_A below which answers are considered equal
Moderate Gap	0.10	Reliability gap for weighted merging
# From mode_selection.py lines 396-489 # For NUMERICAL queries with FINANCIAL_LINE evidence: FINANCIAL_DOMINANCE_THRESHOLD = 0.55  if financial_ratio_A >= 0.55:     return TRUST_A  # Operator A has majority XBRL evidence if financial_ratio_B >= 0.55:     return TRUST_B  # Operator B has majority XBRL evidence  # Standard logic for non-numerical or balanced cases: RELIABILITY_GAP_THRESHOLD = 0.25  if delta_A < 0.10:     return MERGE_EQUAL  # Answers agree closely if reliability_gap > 0.25:     return TRUST_MORE_RELIABLE  # Clear reliability winner if reliability_gap > 0.10:     return MERGE_WEIGHTED  # Weight by reliability return MERGE_EQUAL  # Default
Trust Decision Types
Decision	Description	Use Case
TRUST_A	Use Operator A's answer exclusively	Numerical queries with XBRL dominance
TRUST_B	Use Operator B's answer exclusively	Narrative queries with high quality evidence
MERGE_EQUAL	Average both answers equally	Strong agreement or equal reliability
MERGE_WEIGHTED	Weight by reliability scores	Moderate agreement with reliability gap
CONFLICT	Present both perspectives	Irreconcilable disagreement
 
9. Complete Query Processing Flow
Step-by-Step Flow
●	1. Query Classification: Determine query type (NUMERICAL, CAUSAL, OPINION, etc.) and complexity
●	2. Initialize Strategy: Start with balanced explore_weight = 0.5
●	3. Hop 1 - Independent Exploration:
○	   - Operator A: Seeds from FINANCIAL_LINE, traverses structure edges
○	   - Operator B: Seeds from TEXT_SECTION/NOTE, traverses narrative edges
○	   - Generate answers from each operator's evidence
●	4. Compute Commutator: Calculate Δ(q, 1)
●	5. Apply Convergence Pressure: If Δ_E > 0.8, share top nodes between operators
●	6. Update Strategy: Adjust explore_weight based on divergence and trajectory
●	7. Hop 2+ - Convergence-Aware Exploration:
○	   - Each operator receives other's evidence for convergence rewards
○	   - Edge scoring system penalizes semantic drift and domain isolation
●	8. Check Termination: Evaluate stopping conditions
●	9. Mode Selection: Determine EXPLOIT/ADAPTIVE/EXPLORE based on final state
●	10. Trust Decision: Select which operator(s) to trust for answer generation
●	11. Generate Final Answer: Use appropriate prompt template for mode
Termination Conditions
Condition	Threshold	Description
Max Hops Reached	6 (varies by query type)	Safety limit to prevent infinite loops
Strong Convergence	Δ < 0.25	Operators have converged sufficiently
Answer Agreement	Δ_A < 0.05 (numerical)	Operators produce semantically identical answers
Stabilization	improvement < 0.02	No significant improvement between hops
Rapid Divergence	3 consecutive increasing Δ	Give up on convergence
 
